      {
        "id": 2505883,
        "name": "Ilkka |_ |_| mme",
        "username": "IlkkaL",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/ilkkal/{size}/2504_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-10-21T08:30:24.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>We have been getting together with small group of friends once or twice a year since the beginning of the decade to drink Champagne and eat sushi and cheeses. This time we decided to do a small blind tasting of two BdB and two BdN with the idea of putting wines from quite different price points against each other. While the BdN \u201cflight\u201d was as easy as it gets I actually struggled to decide between the two Chardonnays as the Lenoble really held its own against the considerably pricier Pol Roger. In the end I had a strong suspicion that the riper wine would be the Pol Roger but the wine I actually enjoyed more was the sub-30 \u20ac Lenoble. For something so affordable it had pretty much everything I look for in a Blanc de Blancs, most importantly really great precision. Really looking forward to trying their fancier wines after this.</p>\n<p>Egly-Ouriet is without a doubt one of the best wine producers in the world and this bottle was the best I have had from them thus far. I would have absolutely no problem paying the 110 \u20ac it cost and I think the QPR is actually exceptionally high when compared to many grand marque prestige Champagnes that cost a lot more and demand a decade of ageing before reaching the start of their drinking window. For the fans of Pinot Noir Champagne this is it right here in my books.</p>\n<p>As I knew my friend to be a fan of mature reds I blinded him with the Porta dos Cavaleiros. I had only had the producer\u2019s 100 % Bagas from Bairrada before so did not quite know what to expect but knew that the wines generally age really slowly. However I would have not guessed that an affordable wine from my birth year could be so incredibly youthful.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<strong>NV A. R. Lenoble Champagne Grand Cru Blanc de Blancs Brut</strong> <em>- France, Champagne, Champagne Grand Cru (21.10.2018)</em><br>\nVery bright and pretty on the nose with fresh citrus fruits, bread dough and vanilla along with salty, earthy and smoky tones. Fairly lean - though not thin - on the palate with plenty of freshness and finesse. Dry and thoroughly well-balanced with a very chalky feel to it. Sunshine in a bottle, drinks fantastically well.</li>\n<li>\n<strong>2009 Pol Roger Champagne Blanc de Blancs</strong> <em>- France, Champagne (21.10.2018)</em><br>\nSpicy and ripe-fruited on the nose with some zestiness to it. Beautiful toasty aromas. On the palate quite large-scaled, this is not a skinny aperitif Champagne by any means. Very ripe, despite clearly dry there is a sweet edge to it. Some nice tart tones and high acidity balance the ripeness and richness nicely. Holds its composure very well in the glass. While not as vinous as many grower wines it does have very good volume. A good wine but not quite there yet.</li>\n<li>\n<strong>NV Fleury Pere &amp; Fils Champagne Blanc de Noirs Brut</strong> <em>- France, Champagne (21.10.2018)</em><br>\nRipe, exotic fruits on the nose along with cherry and some toast. Not very detailed nor complex. On the palate dry yet quite rich and with good lift. Lacks depth and complexity but sports quite impeccable balance and nice vinosity. Very gentle and drinkable, if not particularly exciting. Did not manage air very well.</li>\n<li>\n<strong>NV Egly-Ouriet Champagne Grand Cru Blanc de Noirs Les Cray\u00e8res</strong> <em>- France, Champagne, Champagne Grand Cru (21.10.2018)</em><br>\nSmells down right Burgundian with ripe red cherry, plenty of oak and expensive nougat. Amazingly intense expression of fruit, this is downright impressive. On the palate ripe, opulent and hedonistic. The sheer density of it is something to behold. Most definitely more Pinot Noir than Champagne, the bubbles are not very important here. Beautifully red-fruited with hauntingingly delicious spicy notes. Under all the concentration is a very powerful acidic core gives the wine tons of structure and energy. Seems to evolve in the glass for forever.</li>\n<li>\n<strong>NV Eric Rodez Champagne Grand Cru Cuv\u00e9e des Cray\u00e8res</strong> <em>- France, Champagne, Champagne Grand Cru (21.10.2018)</em><br>\nA fresh, fruity nose with notes of apple and crushed rock. A large, dense mousse reveals a dry, saline wine with a nice lively feel. Good volume, not a lightweight by any means. What I struggle with is trying to pinpoint any specific flavors - the wine seems to lack detail and there is not much to connect with here. Perfectly pleasant and drinkable but very easy to forget at the same time.</li>\n<li>\n<strong>1985 Caves S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o D\u00e3o Porta dos Cavaleiros Reserva</strong> <em>- Portugal, Beiras, D\u00e3o (21.10.2018)</em><br>\nAt the age of 33 this has the most impressive color: dark and deep with nothing that could give away its age. On the nose lively blackcurrant fruit, red cherry, old furniture and soy. On the palate medium-bodied yet fleshy. Quite dry but with nice lively dark fruits and solid acidity. Not terribly complex but drinks very well and has not dried out at all. Served blind, people were guessing late-nineties or early 2000s and it\u2019s hard to blame them for thinking so.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Posted from <a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">CellarTracker</a></em></p>",
